reviews.title: NOT FRESH and question ORGANIC
reviews.review_text: I do not recommend purchasing these unless you are going to literally eat them same day or next. Potatoes of all vegetables should have some sort of shelf life...you know when they are really bad is when they shrivel and mold before having the opportunity to start sprouting. I did receive a refund that didn't require me to actually return to the store...which I do appreciate. The whole purpose of having things delivered is to not have to go into the store.

reviews.title: Yucky

It’s like I’m receiving the least desirable foods when delivered, not the freshest. Would be nice if shoppers were a little more discerning when selecting items.

reviews.title: I should have read the reviews first!
reviews.review_text: This potatoes are VERY hard and VERY dry. Bad quality. I practically needed a machete to peel this potatoes. When I picked them up out of the net bag, I noticed they were hard and have no give to them at all. When peeled, the first 1/4 inch of these are white, then once you peel that far down, it is then you see the true orange color of the potatoes. It was likened to whittling wood. They were hard to cut into chunks as well. These are very strange. I don’t know if simmering in water is going to save them. Very much a drought crop and look like they were grown in silica sand. Won’t buy again.

reviews.title: "Walmart Failure on Sweet Potatoes u0026 Refund"
reviews.review_text: I have had enough. I’ve been very patient with Walmart about their sweet potato problem. It has been like this for years. There is just no excuse for continuing to send out sweet potatoes on delivery that are moldy or so rotten they are turning to mush and are dripping liquid and have bugs which took weeks to eradicate. The refund process for this problem used to be seamless. So that took the sting out. Now all of a sudden they are asking for the rotten produce TO BE RETURNED TO THE STORE. This is unreasonable and I seriously doubt they want to COLLECT bug-attracting produce into a place that sells prepared foods in deli and bakery and a restaurant. I have reported it and thought it must be an error in the return process but they keep leaving it set up this way

Don't normally buy organic but I have been for a while. At first they were bright orange, cooked up well and tasted delicious. The last two times the quality was poor. This time they were hard and dirty. Yellow yams mixed in the the orange ones. Very dry and no taste. Won't buy them again. Disappointing!

reviews.title: Perfect small Sweet potato dinner for one
reviews.review_text: The size is great for dinner for one, just pop into the microwave for 4 minutes and they're ready to eat. Sweet enough they don't even need butter. Sweet potato crust no-flour quiche? Thin slice to make a sweet potato crust, just butter or oil a pie plate or sautee pan, line with thin slices, takes about 2-3 layers to cover the pan nicely, then brush on melted butter and cook for 20 minutes at 350 - potatoes should be slightly tender- Filling - I like 4 eggs plus 2 egg whites, 1 bag steamed spinach, a 1/2 cup of milk or favorite substitute, and 2-4 oz feta or Chevre goat cheese, 1/4 tsp salt, 1/2 sauteed onion (optional), a pinch of red pepper flakes, then cook for 35 minutes on 375 - serves 4, and reheats well. (It's also a great crust to fill with your favorite meatloaf!)
Do not buy these. 3 out of 4 times they are visibly old. The packaging date is usually 3 weeks to more than a month old. Go to Sprouts for your produce and meat. It's worth it.

BJ's club sells these for less than $2 for the same sized bag. So the profit taking must be insane. No wonder they stay on the shelf long enough to go bad as other reviews have stated. It's a shame.

reviews.title: Rotten food in my order
reviews.review_text: Curbside order. Getting produce this way is ALWAYS sketchy however today was unacceptable. The guy that was loading my car said...oohhh these are wet, something spilled on them. I brushed him off with- Oh they're potatoes I can rinse them..right? I get home and unload, all the while smelling something oddly sweet, beer-like - no beer in my order. The sweet potato bag isn't just "wet", the potatoes are rotten. Not just the corner.. most of them in the bag. This speaks to extreme carelessness. Who ever "picked" the produce for my order either didn't care that rotten food went out or never took half a second to even bother checking. These rotting potatoes were literally thrown in the same bag as my apples. Those might have been fine had they not been cut up and bruised due to heavier items thrown on top of them. Now they do will be thrown out as well, after sitting in the soup of rotten potatoes.

The potatoes were delivered I paid a seven dollar delivery fee to the driver. Two of the potatoes in the bag completely rotten and now Walmart wants me to return the bag to the store in order to get a refund, I find that ridiculous find the store as I pay the tip

reviews.title: The good and the bad about organic potatoes
reviews.review_text: Organic potatoes tend to rot faster because of the pollution in the environment. Organic produce go through many process of tests to ensure they are purity of it. Farmers do not use pesticide nor unnatural fertilizer. It came from the care of the Almighty. Conventional potatoes do not need to go through many tests. It is easier to grow but farmers use many unnatural pesticides to protect from pestilence and chemical fertilizer to grow it fast. Overall, organic produce is healthier than the conventional. They are only few organic produce in the shelves because farmers quit farming but work for private and government offices.
